NGO HUB Portal
Connect. Collaborate. Impact.
A Web-Based Platform for NGO Management, Collaboration & Donor Transparency
1. Project Overview
NGO HUB Portal is a comprehensive, single-page web application designed to bring NGOs
(Non-Governmental Organizations), corporate partners, and donors onto one unified digital platform. The
project addresses a real-world problem: NGOs working on social causes such as healthcare, women's
welfare, river conservation, tree plantation, water management, agriculture, and education often operate
in isolation, with limited visibility into their own impact and little structured way to collaborate with funding
partners. NGO HUB Portal solves this by combining partner management, fund tracking, impact analytics,
donation handling, grant tracking, an internal news feed, an event calendar, NGO-to-company
collaboration, and a public transparency dashboard, all within a single, modern, responsive web interface.
The platform is built entirely with front-end web technologies (HTML, CSS and JavaScript), making it
lightweight, portable, and easy to deploy without requiring a dedicated backend server for its core
demonstration features. It uses browser-based local storage for persistence and integrates third-party
libraries for spreadsheet parsing and interactive mapping.
2. Objectives
l Provide a centralised dashboard where companies/CSR teams can discover, verify, and manage
partnerships with multiple NGOs.
l Allow NGOs to register, get verified through a structured document-upload workflow, and showcase
their work transparently.
l Enable donors and partner companies to track exactly how funds are utilised through visual analytics
and statistics.
l Visualise the geographical spread of NGO activity and field impact using an interactive map.
l Support real-world NGO operational data (medical camps, women's welfare, river clean-ups, tree
plantation, water projects, agriculture, education, health) by ingesting and analysing uploaded Excel
datasets.
l Facilitate communication and resource sharing between NGOs and partner companies through an
internal collaboration and messaging module.
l Build donor trust through a public transparency view of fund utilisation and campaign spending.
3. Key Modules & Features
3.1 Authentication & Onboarding
l Landing page with sign-in flow and a guided 'How to use' walkthrough for first-time users.
l NGO verification workflow with step-based progress tracking and document upload (registration
certificates, etc.).
l Status-based routing that automatically directs verified, pending, or rejected NGOs to the correct
page.
3.2 Company / Partner Dashboard
l A tabbed dashboard covering Partners, Impact Analytics, Donations, Grant Tracker, News Feed,
Event Calendar, Collaborate, Alerts, and Transparency — nine functional tabs in one workspace.
l Partner directory listing all onboarded NGOs with quick access to each NGO's individual profile page.
l Ability to add new NGOs and new events/campaigns directly through modal forms.
3.3 Impact Analytics Engine
One of the most technically significant parts of the project is the data-driven impact analytics engine. The
portal allows Excel (.xlsx) datasets to be uploaded for a specific NGO event/campaign, which are then
parsed in the browser (using the SheetJS/xlsx.js library) and automatically routed to a domain-specific
statistics renderer depending on the nature of the data.
l Dedicated statistical processing modules for: Medical Camps, Women's Welfare, River Conservation,
Tree Plantation, Water Projects, Agriculture, General Welfare, Education, and Health datasets.
l Drag-and-drop file upload with preview, validation, and the ability to clear/re-upload data per
campaign.
l Automatic column detection logic to intelligently map uploaded spreadsheet columns to the expected
statistical fields for each domain.
l Aggregated cross-NGO charts: Funds by NGO, Campaign Spend by NGO, Campaigns per NGO, and
Fund Utilisation percentage.
l A predictive insights feature (renderCompanyPrediction) that projects trends for a company's partner
NGOs based on historical data.
3.4 Interactive Impact Map
An interactive map (built with Leaflet.js) plots every NGO's location, colour-coded by category (e.g. health,
environment, education, welfare). Users can click an NGO to fly to its location on the map, giving
stakeholders an immediate geographic sense of where field activity is concentrated.
3.5 Donations & Fund Management
l Donation modal with preset and custom donation amounts per NGO.
l Running donation totals and a donation history log.
l Fund recalculation logic that keeps a live, accurate strip showing total funds raised/available,
formatted in Indian currency notation (INR), including short-form formatting for large numbers.
3.6 Grant Tracker
l NGOs/companies can submit grant applications through a structured modal form.
l Grant status management (e.g. pending, approved, rejected) with persisted state.
3.7 News Feed & Event Calendar
l An internal social-style news feed where updates can be posted, filtered by type, and liked.
l A full event calendar with month-by-month navigation, used to track NGO and company events and
global campaigns.
3.8 Collaboration & Resource Sharing
l A messaging interface allowing companies to select an NGO and exchange messages directly within
the portal.
l A shared resource board where NGOs and partners can post and browse shared resources relevant
to ongoing campaigns.
3.9 Alerts & Notifications
A notification centre surfaces system and activity alerts (e.g. new verification requests, grant updates),
with user-configurable alert preferences.
3.10 Public Transparency Dashboard
A transparency module is presented for public/donor consumption, summarising how funds have been
raised and spent across NGOs and campaigns — reinforcing donor trust and accountability, which is one
of the biggest pain points for NGOs seeking long-term partnerships.
4. Technical Implementation
l Front-end: Pure HTML5, CSS3 (custom design system using CSS variables for a consistent dark,
glassmorphism-inspired theme) and vanilla JavaScript — no heavy framework dependency, making
the app fast and easy to host anywhere.
l Typography & Design: Custom design tokens (colour palette, spacing, border-radius, shadows)
defined via CSS variables; Google Fonts ('Syne' for headings, 'DM Sans' for body) for a modern,
professional look; responsive grid layouts for mobile and desktop.
l Data Persistence: Browser localStorage used to persist companies, NGOs, donations, grants, news
posts, alerts, and access records between sessions without a backend database.
l Spreadsheet Processing: SheetJS (xlsx.full.min.js) integrated for parsing uploaded Excel files
entirely client-side.
l Mapping: Leaflet.js integrated for rendering the interactive, colour-coded impact map with markers
and fly-to navigation.
l Application Architecture: A single-page application (SPA) pattern, where distinct 'pages' (Index,
Home/Dashboard, Map, Company Profile, Ad/Campaign Detail, Verification) are shown/hidden via a
central showPage() router, and dashboard content is further split into switchable tabs using a
switchTab() controller.
l State Management: Custom JavaScript functions handle saving/loading companies and access
records, recalculating funds, and rendering each UI section reactively whenever underlying data
changes.
5. Skills & Concepts Demonstrated
l Front-end engineering: responsive UI/UX design, component-style page/tab architecture,
modal-driven workflows, and design-system thinking.
l Client-side data engineering: parsing, validating, and transforming spreadsheet data into structured
statistics across nine distinct social-impact domains.
l Geospatial visualisation: integrating and customising a mapping library for real-world location-based
reporting.
l State and persistence management in the browser without a backend.
l Designing for multiple stakeholder roles (NGOs, corporate/CSR partners, donors/public) within one
cohesive product.
l End-to-end product thinking: from onboarding and verification, to operational dashboards, to
public-facing transparency reporting.
6. Real-World Relevance & Impact
NGO HUB Portal mirrors a genuine gap in the social impact sector: the lack of a single, trustworthy
platform connecting NGOs with corporate CSR partners and donors, backed by verifiable, data-driven
reporting. By combining structured NGO verification, granular impact analytics across multiple welfare
domains, geospatial visualisation, and a public transparency layer, the project demonstrates a practical,
deployable solution that could meaningfully improve trust, accountability, and collaboration in the NGO
ecosystem. The project reflects a strong interest in building socially impactful, assistive technology — an
interest that has also shaped other independent work, such as IoT-based assistive and
posture-monitoring devices.
7. Conclusion
NGO HUB Portal is a complete, feature-rich, single-page web application that goes well beyond a typical
front-end project: it implements multi-domain data analytics, geospatial visualisation, donation and grant
workflows, collaboration tools, and a public transparency dashboard, all wrapped in a polished, modern
UI. It demonstrates strong full-stack-adjacent front-end engineering skills, an ability to design for multiple
user roles, and a clear focus on solving a meaningful, real-world social impact problem through
technology.
